<h1>Cellular Automata: Complex Patterns from Simple Rules</h1>
<h2>David Eppstein, University Studies 3, Spring 2007</h2>

<p>Cellular automata such as Conway's famous "Game of Life" are systems
for describing complex and changing visual patterns based on very simple
computational rules. In this seminar, we'll see the kinds of patterns
that can be generated with cellular automata, find out about computer
programs for exploring cellular automaton rules, and learn about how
these systems can model phenomena from the physical world.</p>

<p>The course will meet Mondays, 11:00 - 11:50, in CS 360D. Grading will
be attendance-based.</p>

<p>Tentative Schedule of Topics:</p>
<ul>
<li>Week 1. Introduction: pretty patterns from simple rules.
<a href="http://psoup.math.wisc.edu/kitchen.html">Primordial soup kitchen</a> galleries: <a href="http://psoup.math.wisc.edu/bakers12.html">1</a>, <a href="http://psoup.math.wisc.edu/special2.html">2</a>. <a href="http://psoup.math.wisc.edu/java/jcca.html">Cyclic
cellular automata</a>.</li>
<li>Week 2. <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conway's_Game_of_Life">Conway's Game
of Life</a>. See <a href="http://www.ibiblio.org/lifepatterns/">Alan
Hensel's Life applet</a> or <a
href="http://golly.sourceforge.net/">Golly</a> for many
interesting patterns in this system.</li>
<li>Week 3. <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life-like_cellular_automaton">Life-like
rules</a> and <a href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~eppstein/ca/wolfram.html">Wolfram's classification</a>.</li>
<li>Week 4. One-dimensional cellular automata, <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traffic_flow">traffic modeling</a>,
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_184">rule 184</a>, and ballistic annihilation.</li>
<li>Week 5. <a href="http://www.walenz.org/vonNeumann/index.html">Von Neumann's theory of self-reproducing
automata</a>, additive rules, <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierpinski_triangle">Sierpinski
triangles</a>, and <a
href="http://www.ics.uci.edu/~eppstein/ca/replicators/">rules with
simple replicators</a>.
<li>Week 6. <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wireworld">Wireworld</a>, <a
href="http://www.quinapalus.com/wi-index.html">circuit</a> <a
href="http://www.maa.org/editorial/mathgames/mathgames_05_24_04.html">simulation</a>,
and <a href="http://rendell-attic.org/gol/tmdetails.htm">Life circuitry</a></li>
<li>Week 7. <a href="http://www.collidoscope.com/modernca/reversablerules.html">Reversible cellular automata</a>. <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loschmidt's_paradox">The paradox of
locally time-symmetric dynamics leading to a global increase of entropy
over time</a>. <a
href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lfQtREQ33vw&mode=related&search=">Pool
ball dynamics</a>
and <a href="http://www.cell-auto.com/bbm/2d/index.html">CA simulations
of pool balls</a>. Reversible CA construction techniques: <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_order_cellular_automaton">2nd
order CA</a> and <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_cellular_automaton">block-partitioning
CA</a>. <a href="http://hex.alife.co.uk/diffusion/">Simulated
diffusion</a>. <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garden_of_Eden_pattern">The search
for the Garden of Eden</a>.
<li>Week 8. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_110_cellular_automaton">Rule</a> <a href="http://delta.cs.cinvestav.mx/~mcintosh/comun/RULE110W/node1.html">110</a></li>
<li>Week 9. No class (Memorial day holiday)</li>
<li>Week 10. Course evaluations</li>
</ul>
</body>
